accessibility.text: How do we solve problems recursively?
How do we solve problems recursively?
Imagine the worst case possible: the thing youre looking for isnt in the list (100,000 elements).
Sequential search:
You will look at all 100,000 elements before being able to determine the value isnt there.
Binary search (example run through):
Look at index 50,000, too big, search in [0, 49,999]
Look at index 25,000, too big, search in [0, 24,999]
Look at index 12,500, too small, search in [12,501, 24,999]
Look at index 18,750, too small, search in [18,751, 24,999]
Look at index 21,875, too big, search in [18,751, 21,875]
Look at index 20,313, too big, search in [18,751, 20,312]
Look at index 19,531, too small, search in [19,532, 20,312]
Look at index 19,922, too big, search in [19,532, 19,921]
Look at index 19,726, too big, search in [19,532, 19,725]
Look at index 19,629, too big, search in [19,532, 19,628]
Look at index 19,580, too big, search in [19,532, 19,579]
Look at index 19,555, too small, search in [19,556, 19,579]
Look at index 19,567, too small, search in [19,568, 19,579]
Look at index 19,573, too small, search in [19,574, 19,579]
Look at index 19,576, too small, search in [19,577, 19,579]
Look at index 19,578, too small, search in [19,579, 19,579]
Look at index 19,579, too small, search in [19,580, 19,579] - WAIT A SECOND!
It took 17 passes to figure out that the key was not in the list. That is substantially faster than 100,000 passes!
